Let me analyze the gdv_decode_frame function for optimization opportunities:

1. Bottleneck Analysis:
- The function has two main parts: decompression (switch case) and frame data copying (final loops)
- The frame copying loops at the end are performance critical as they process every pixel
- Current implementation uses nested loops with per-pixel operations
- The scaling cases (gdv->scale_v/h) have different optimized paths but could be improved

2. Key Observations:
- The non-scaling case (no scale_v/h) can use memcpy for each line instead of per-pixel copy
- The scaling cases can be optimized by processing 4/8 pixels at a time when possible
- The didx/sidx calculations can be simplified by pre-calculating line increments
- The final pixel handling in scaling cases can be minimized

3. Optimization Choice:
The most impactful optimization would be to optimize the non-scaling case (most common path) by:
- Replacing the nested pixel-by-pixel loop with memcpy for each line
- Pre-calculating line increments to avoid repeated calculations
- Keeping the scaling cases similar but with better loop structure

